Issue.SpecificIssue: NETWORK suppports improvements to the Freedom of Information Act to improve the quality of information available to citizens. NETWORK supports passage of the Voting Rights Amendment Act of 2014 to protect voting rights for all citizens.

NETWORK supports Executive Order 13650 which improves the safety and security of chemical plants in America. NETWORK suppports granting Endangered Species Protection to monarch butterflies. NETWORK supports protecting the Artic National Wildlife Refuge and passing a comprehensive conservation plan to achieve this goal.

NETWORK supports removing sequester limits for the domestic discretionary budget and increasing spending on programs that invest in human potential. NETWORK suppports funding programs aimed at encouraging conflict prevention and the protection of humanitarian assistance.

S. 2260: The Expire Act: NETWORK opposed this extension of tax benefits to corporations because they are not paid for and they do not provide adequate relief to people living in poverty. NETWORK supports a permanent and enhanced Earned Income Tax Credit for working families and childless individuals. NETWORK supports a permanent and refundable Child Tax Credit.
NETWORK suppports extending full funding for the Children's Health Insurance Program.
NETWORK supports using science as the basis of food selection for WIC programs and as such opposes the inclusion of white potatoes in the program.

NETWORK supports comprehensive immigration reform with a pathway to citizenship. NETWORK strongly supports Pres. Obama's Executive Action providing relief from deportation to immigrants living in America. NETWORK supports spending for and legal protection of unaccompanied children from Central America. NETWORK supports strengthening human rights efforts and funding international institutions that strengthen the rule of law.NETWORK opposes funding for detention centers for immigrant families and suppports the use of alternatives to detention (ATDs).

NETWORK opposes extension of fast track authority unless significantly modified to give Congress more authority over trade issues. NETWORK supports increased environmental and labor protections in the Transpacific Partnership agreement and opposes inclusion of an investment chapter and increased intellectual property protection for pharmaceutical products.

NETWORK supports S. 3711, a bill that would restore whistleblower protections for intelligence community contractors who disclose fraud, waste, abuse, gross mismanagement or a violation of law. NETWORK supports recommendations to enhance fiscal responsibility and strengthen accountablity in defense programs. NETWORK opposes the use of spending through Section 1033 to militarize Law Enforcement Agencies (LEAs).

Issue.SpecificIssue:
On behalf of 56 religious and human rights organizations and leaders of varying faiths, including the client, who signed a multi-faith letter to the President, made contacts to urge U.S. leaders to set immediate and long term goals for intervention in the Syrian-Iraqi conflict -- to protect Christians and other religious and ethnic minorities and stop the crimes against humanity that threaten their lives and fundamental rights. This is necessary to fulfill our foundational commitments as a nation to intervene to protect victims of genocide, ethnic cleansing, and crimes against humanity. As the President stated at the 2014 National Prayer Breakfast, the U.S.: "believe[s] in the inherent dignity of every human being -- dignity that no earthly power can take away. And central to that dignity is freedom of religion," "promoting religious freedom is a key objective of U.S. foreign policy," and "in Syria, it means ensuring a place for all people -- Alawites and Sunni, Shia and Christian." Overcoming the ISIS extremist and fascist ideology and those who promote it is the great challenge of the 21st century. We hope the U.S. will play a central role in this struggle as it did in the 20th century struggles against fascism and communism, which also used anti-religious ideas to attain their goals. The behavior and ideas emanating from Syria and Iraq are something that cannot be tolerated by civilized nations and that must be combatted with a full commitment by the U.S. and other governments, religious and ethnic groups, and religious freedom and civil society advocates.
On behalf of 75 religious and human rights organizations and leaders of varying faiths, including the client, who signed a multi-faith letter to members of Congress, made contacts to recommend with the utmost enthusiasm the immediate confirmation of Rabbi David Saperstein as the new Ambassador-at-Large for International Religious Freedom. Amidst rising restrictions on religious freedom worldwide, and an ever-deepening crisis in Syria and Iraq, the United States needs every possible tool in its toolkit. Rabbi Saperstein not only knows the issue, but he knows Washington and the world. He understands religious freedom as a multidisciplinary issue that cuts across human rights, economics, security, counter-terrorism, media, academia, business, and other relevant sectors. And he has almost universal support from across the theological and political spectrum. We urged Congress to send a signal to the world that we take this issue seriously, and as integral to the solutions that our global challenges demand; and to confirm Rabbi David Saperstein as the new Ambassador-at-Large for International Religious Freedom swiftly, so that this vital position is not left vacant.
The Senate confirmed Saperstein by a roll call vote of 62-35.
On behalf of 81 religious and human rights organizations and leaders of varying faiths, including the client, who signed a multi-faith letter to members of Congress to urge them to support swift passage of H.R. 4653, the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom (USCIRF) Reauthorization Act of 2014, made contacts to urge members of Congress to ensure the end-of-year spending package (the Cromnibus) included funding for USCIRF through September 30, 2015.
The end-of-year spending package (Cromnibus) provided $3,500,000 for USCIRF: Provided, That if the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom is authorized beyond September 30, 2014, this amount will remain available until September 30, 2015. So the appropriation was not sufficient.
Then made contacts in support of H.R. 5816, a bill to extend the authorization for the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom. This bill would amend the International Religious Freedom Act of 1998 to extend through FY2015 the authorization for the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom.
H.R. 5816 was introduced in the House on December 9, 2014; passed the House without objection on December 10; passed the Senate without amendment by Unanimous Consent on December 15; was signed by the President, and became Public Law 113-271 on December 18.

Issue.SpecificIssue: Passed in House on July 24, 2014., H.R. 3136, the Advancing Competency-Based Education Demonstration Project Act, sponsored by Representatives Matt Salmon (AZ-05) and Jared Polis (CO-02) would increase access and affordability in higher education by allowing institutions the flexibility to provide a degree that is based on a students knowledge and skills instead of seat time.

Sequestration: University of Arizona joined our fellow Institutions of Higher Education in asking Congress to stop the sequester which is planned for reinstatement in FY16. The impact of sequestration on the University of Arizona for FY13 was a minimum of $15M.

America COMPETES Reauthorization: (America Creating Opportunities to Meaningfully Promote Excellence in Technology, Education and Science Act of 2007). Current authorization expires this year, congressional action expected prior, with a focus on focusing support for the National Science Foundation and other agencies. During this quarter, UA began to prepare for a push in the 114th Congress on COMPETES and other federal research related funding.

Graduate Medical Education (HR 1201 Training Tomorrows Doctors Today Act - Shock/Schwartz): AZ faces a physician shortage that is most acute in the primary care field. In 2010, the State ranked 41 in active primary care physicians per capita and 35 in primary care residents. AZ is already funding more 150 residency slots with no Federal support (nearly all UA), but is still approximately 850 positions short of the national per capita average. UA supports legislation such as HR 1201 for the next Congre.

Federal Research Funding: UA advocated for sufficient appropriations for key federal funding agencies, such as the National Institutes for Health, the National Science Foundation, NASA (HR2787 and S1429), Department of Energy (Office of Science), DHS (University Programs), USDA (NIFA), Department of Commerce (NOAA), and Department of Interior (USGS). This process was closed with the passage of the "FY15 Crominibus".

ADAPT Act: UA supported this bill, (still under Committee review) which would, among other things, amend the law to create a pathway for the prompt approval of antibacterial and antifungal drugs intended to treat serious or life-threatening diseases or conditions. The ADAPT Act is viewed as successor legislation to the Generating Antibiotics Incentives Now Act (GAIN Act), and would be particularly helpful fo researchers studying Valley Fever.

National Defense Authorization Act and Defense Appropriations (HR2397/S1329): UA worked to support defense basic and applied research funding levels, including DARPA, AFOSR, ARL, and ONR agency funding and the MINERVA social science program. UA supported passage of the NDAA on 12/12/14.

Higher Education Act Reauthorization: legislation to reauthorize is expected in the 113th Congress, and UA has joined our fellow IHE's in identifying issues of possible concern, including Title IV provisions related to federal financial aid and the Title VI foreign language centers; and access to financial aid, possible redress of the GI Bill not counting as federal aid under Title IV, along with a recalculation of the 90/10 rule. UA has created a campus-wide HEA Reauthorization Task Force to address HEA Reauth.

NASA appropriations legislation: HR2787 House Commerce Justice Science Appropriations, S1329 Senate Commerce Justice Science appropriations advocating for sufficient funding levels for NASA overall, NASA Science Mission Directorate, Planetary and Earth Science, and NASA Space Grant. UA supported the level of NASA funding in the FY15 "Cromnibus".

House (HR 2687) and Senate(S1317) NASA Reauthorization Bills: UA advocates for appropriate funding for university-competable missions, such as the New Frontiers and Discovery-class missions, and expressed concern over implementation of Administration plans for STEM Education programs consolidation.

Veteran Education Empowerment Act (HR 5589)(Introd by Rep. Frankel, co-sponsored by Reps. Bilirakis and Takano) The Veteran Education Empowerment Act would award four-year grants to institutions of higher education (IHEs) to establish, maintain, and improve a veteran student center.

Title VI Centers (International Education): UA advocates for the Title VI centers program at US Department of Education: UA hosts 3 such Centers (Center for Educational Resources in Culture, Language and Literacy, the Center for Latin American Studies, and the Center for Middle Eastern Studies). UA also prepared to lobby on this matter in the coming Reauthorization of the Higher Education Act, including in the 114th Congress.

UA advocates for the following specific programs within the various federal agencies with federal appropriations: DHS University Programs: UA advocates for sufficient support for this account due to the UA-based DHS Center of Excellence for Border Security, USGS: UA hosts the USGS-funded Water Resources Research Center (WRRCs), NASA Space Grant education program (UA is the Space Grant host in Arizona), Dept of Energy Office of Science (UA hosts an Energy Frontier Research Center).

S. 744: Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act. UA supports DREAM Act provisions in S7.44, and recommended fixes to various clauses related to H-1B visas and other sections supporting international education. During this quarter, UA worked with Members of the Arizona delegation on this bill.
